# Testing Protocol for Claude Code

## Critical Rule
**ALWAYS test, validate and verify with browser after each prompt that modifies code.**

## Why This Matters
- Hot reload may not pick up all changes
- Runtime errors may not show in build logs
- Visual/functional bugs only appear in browser
- User experience is the ultimate validation

## Testing Checklist

### After Code Changes
1. ✅ Wait for Next.js hot reload to complete
2. ✅ Check browser console for errors
3. ✅ Verify visual rendering is correct
4. ✅ Test user interactions (clicks, form inputs, etc.)
5. ✅ Check Network tab for API errors
6. ✅ Validate data flow end-to-end

### For UI Component Changes
- [ ] Open page in browser
- [ ] Interact with changed components
- [ ] Check for runtime errors in console
- [ ] Verify styling/layout
- [ ] Test edge cases (empty states, errors, etc.)

### For API Changes
- [ ] Test with curl/Postman
- [ ] Check server logs for errors
- [ ] Verify response format
- [ ] Test error handling

### For State Management
- [ ] Verify initial state
- [ ] Test state updates
- [ ] Check for race conditions
- [ ] Validate cleanup on unmount

## Common Pitfalls
- ❌ Trusting "No TypeScript errors" without browser test
- ❌ Assuming hot reload worked without verification
- ❌ Not checking console for warnings
- ❌ Skipping edge case testing

## This Document
- Location: `.memory-bank/testing_protocol.md`
- Purpose: Ensure rigorous testing of all code changes
- Updated: 2025-11-02
